{"parentUuid":"8285d114-a4d8-45a8-9d8e-f2f6784d19f4","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aac7737a5d3b7d6e7","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Cd7cacAniF9GhFbsQW7Uo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0182mmZuaFoSvmyDgrnHnmD7","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/kamilner/tamarin-cleanroom/PROTOCOL.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":14732,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":14732,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011Cd7caahErAdVB4rGyKk9P","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"9e299522-b296-42b4-96c8-6811b30ffad2","timestamp":"2026-07-17T12:16:44.072Z","effort":"xhigh","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/home/kamilner/tamarin-rs","sessionId":"57f8e1bc-d495-4b36-93c0-033347d5034a","version":"2.1.212","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"9e299522-b296-42b4-96c8-6811b30ffad2","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"a3a1890b-4356-4bf6-b523-7534e72cab2b","agentId":"aac7737a5d3b7d6e7","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0182mmZuaFoSvmyDgrnHnmD7","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Clean-room reimplementation protocol — tamarin-rs relicensing\n2\t\n3\tPurpose: independently recreate three modules of tamarin-rs (wellformedness\n4\tchecker, graph/dot pipeline, web layer) without access to GPL-covered\n5\texpression, so the results are original works relicensable at will.\n6\t\n7\t## Rooms\n8\t- DIRTY ROOM (Kevin Milner + main-session assistant): has read the GPL Haskell\n9\t  source and the ported Rust modules. Produces only: interoperability headers\n10\t  (type surfaces, entry-point signatures, comments stripped), oracle wrappers,\n11\t  and behavioral bug reports. Never contributes implementation text.\n12\t- CLEAN ROOM (isolated agents, one per cluster): receive ONLY the materials\n13\t  listed per cluster below. Their complete tool-call transcripts are retained\n14\t  as evidence of non-access.\n15\t\n16\t## Clean-room materials (exhaustive)\n17\t1. This protocol, the cluster SPEC.md, and interface/ headers (type surfaces +\n18\t   boundary signatures only).\n19\t2. Black-box oracles: `wf_oracle.sh` (runs the compiled Haskell binary on an\n20\t   input file), `hs_server.sh` (serves a theory in the Haskell web UI for HTTP\n21\t   probing), pre-captured oracle outputs (oracle/captures/,\n22\t   oracle/captured_responses/), and GPL example .spthy files used solely as\n23\t   observation INPUTS.\n24\t3. Public Rust toolchain and general documentation.\n25\t\n26\t## Forbidden to the clean room\n27\t- Reading ANY file under /home/kamilner/tamarin-rs/ — source, comments, git\n28\t  history — with the sole exceptions of executing the oracle scripts and\n29\t  reading oracle/captured_responses/ (captured program OUTPUT, not source).\n30\t- Fetching tamarin-prover source, docs describing its internals, or its GitHub.\n31\t- Reproducing any tamarin-prover implementation detail from model memory:\n32\t  every behavior must be derived from the oracle, the captures, or the SPEC.\n33\t  Exact output strings (warning texts, DOT syntax, HTML) MUST be taken from\n34\t  observed oracle output — that is compatibility content, not expression.\n35\t\n36\t## Audit & integration (after implementation)\n37\t1. Transcript audit: verify from the retained agent transcripts that no\n38\t   forbidden path was accessed.\n39\t2. Similarity audit: a reviewer (may see both sides) compares the clean code\n40\t   against the Haskell originals; flagged similarities are sent back as\n41\t   redo-instructions, never patched directly.\n42\t3. Behavioral acceptance: byte-parity corpus must pass.\n43\t4. Integration: dirty room may write thin adapters and mechanical renames to\n44\t   fit the workspace API, but must not transplant logic from the replaced\n45\t   modules. The replaced modules are deleted; their GPL-pending headers go\n46\t   with them (history retains them under GPL).\n47\t"}]},"uuid":"0b610e11-0295-4122-9f18-8ed1404d8a47","timestamp":"2026-07-17T12:16:44.084Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/kamilner/tamarin-cleanroom/PROTOCOL.md","content":"# Clean-room reimplementation protocol — tamarin-rs relicensing\n\nPurpose: independently recreate three modules of tamarin-rs (wellformedness\nchecker, graph/dot pipeline, web layer) without access to GPL-covered\nexpression, so the results are original works relicensable at will.\n\n## Rooms\n- DIRTY ROOM (Kevin Milner + main-session assistant): has read the GPL Haskell\n  source and the ported Rust modules. Produces only: interoperability headers\n  (type surfaces, entry-point signatures, comments stripped), oracle wrappers,\n  and behavioral bug reports. Never contributes implementation text.\n- CLEAN ROOM (isolated agents, one per cluster): receive ONLY the materials\n  listed per cluster below. Their complete tool-call transcripts are retained\n  as evidence of non-access.\n\n## Clean-room materials (exhaustive)\n1. This protocol, the cluster SPEC.md, and interface/ headers (type surfaces +\n   boundary signatures only).\n2. Black-box oracles: `wf_oracle.sh` (runs the compiled Haskell binary on an\n   input file), `hs_server.sh` (serves a theory in the Haskell web UI for HTTP\n   probing), pre-captured oracle outputs (oracle/captures/,\n   oracle/captured_responses/), and GPL example .spthy files used solely as\n   observation INPUTS.\n3. Public Rust toolchain and general documentation.\n\n## Forbidden to the clean room\n- Reading ANY file under /home/kamilner/tamarin-rs/ — source, comments, git\n  history — with the sole exceptions of executing the oracle scripts and\n  reading oracle/captured_responses/ (captured program OUTPUT, not source).\n- Fetching tamarin-prover source, docs describing its internals, or its GitHub.\n- Reproducing any tamarin-prover implementation detail from model memory:\n  every behavior must be derived from the oracle, the captures, or the SPEC.\n  Exact output strings (warning texts, DOT syntax, HTML) MUST be taken from\n  observed oracle output — that is compatibility content, not expression.\n\n## Audit & integration (after implementation)\n1. Transcript audit: verify from the retained agent transcripts that no\n   forbidden path was accessed.\n2. Similarity audit: a reviewer (may see both sides) compares the clean code\n   against the Haskell originals; flagged similarities are sent back as\n   redo-instructions, never patched directly.\n3. Behavioral acceptance: byte-parity corpus must pass.\n4. Integration: dirty room may write thin adapters and mechanical renames to\n   fit the workspace API, but must not transplant logic from the replaced\n   modules. The replaced modules are deleted; their GPL-pending headers go\n   with them (history retains them under GPL).\n","numLines":47,"startLine":1,"totalLines":47}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"9e299522-b296-42b4-96c8-6811b30ffad2","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/home/kamilner/tamarin-rs","sessionId":"57f8e1bc-d495-4b36-93c0-033347d5034a","version":"2.1.212","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"0b610e11-0295-4122-9f18-8ed1404d8a47","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aac7737a5d3b7d6e7","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Cd7cacAniF9GhFbsQW7Uo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01U6yfk6jSicq7N3bvTfcLNw","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/kamilner/tamarin-cleanroom/wellformedness/AUDIT.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":14732,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":420,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":14732},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":420,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":14732,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":14732,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011Cd7caahErAdVB4rGyKk9P","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"f7ce944e-e0cc-4459-9b56-e427eed09195","timestamp":"2026-07-17T12:16:44.184Z","effort":"xhigh","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/home/kamilner/tamarin-rs","sessionId":"57f8e1bc-d495-4b36-93c0-033347d5034a","version":"2.1.212","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"f7ce944e-e0cc-4459-9b56-e427eed09195","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"a3a1890b-4356-4bf6-b523-7534e72cab2b","agentId":"aac7737a5d3b7d6e7","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01U6yfk6jSicq7N3bvTfcLNw","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Similarity audit — wellformedness cluster (`wf-clean`)\n2\t\n3\tAuditor role: clean-room similarity review. I read both the clean side and the\n4\tGPL Haskell originals (and, as a secondary leak check, the replaced Rust module\n5\t`crates/tamarin-parser/src/wf.rs`). Method: abstraction–filtration–comparison.\n6\t\n7\t- CLEAN SIDE: `workspace/wf-clean/src/{pretty,report,checks,formula,lib}.rs`\n8\t  (`ast.rs` is the provided interface header — not audited).\n9\t- HASKELL: `tamarin-prover/lib/theory/src/Theory/Tools/Wellformedness.hs`\n10\t  (+ its pretty-printing dependencies).\n11\t- INTERFACE GIVEN TO CLEAN ROOM: `interface/required_api.md`,\n12\t  `interface/ast_types.rs`, `SPEC.md`.\n13\t- CLEAN-ROOM EVIDENCE OF DERIVATION: `workspace/QUERIES.log` (per-probe oracle\n14\t  interaction log), `workspace/BEHAVIOR.md` (inferred behavioral spec),\n15\t  `oracle/captures/*.out` (37 pre-captured oracle outputs).\n16\t\n17\t## Verdict\n18\t\n19\t**PASS. No violations survive filtration.** Every clean/Haskell (or\n20\tclean/wf.rs) similarity resolves to one of the three filtered categories:\n21\t(a) a name or signature explicitly listed in `required_api.md`; (b) an exact\n22\tmessage string present in observed oracle output (captures) or logged as a live\n23\toracle observation in `QUERIES.log`/`BEHAVIOR.md`; or (c) structure forced by\n24\tthe `ast_types.rs` data model or by the block/underline output format.\n25\t\n26\tThe clean code additionally *diverges* from `wf.rs` at every point the interface\n27\tdoes not constrain (see §6), which is positive evidence of independent\n28\tderivation rather than reproduction. One **process caveat** (not a clean-side\n29\tauthorship violation, no redo) is recorded in §7: the interface header transmits\n30\ta port-specific function decomposition to the clean room.\n31\t\n32\t---\n33\t\n34\t## 1. report.rs\n35\t\n36\t- `WfError { topic: String, message: String }`, `impl WfError::new(topic: impl\n37\t  Into<String>, message: impl Into<String>)`, and `pub type WfReport =\n38\t  Vec<WfError>` (report.rs:7-22) are **byte-for-byte the surface in\n39\t  `required_api.md:4-6`**. Haskell models this as `type WfError = (Topic, Doc)` /\n40\t  `type WfErrorReport = [WfError]` (Wellformedness.hs:112-114). The struct field\n41\t  name `message` and the shortened `WfReport` come from the interface header, not\n42\t  from Haskell (which has an unnamed `Doc` and `WfErrorReport`).\n43\t  → **Filtered: API names given in interface docs.**\n44\t- `underline_topic` (report.rs:29-33) renders `title + \"\\n\" + \"=\"*n`. Haskell\n45\t  `underlineTopic` (Wellformedness.hs:168-171) and `wf.rs:400-408` BOTH append a\n46\t  trailing `\"\\n\"`; the clean version does **not** — it assembles the blank line\n47\t  between header and body in `render_block`/`render_report` instead. Divergence\n48\t  from both prior implementations; behavior (the `=` underline) is observable.\n49\t  → **Filtered (observed); note the divergence as independence evidence.**\n50\t- `SUCCESS_LINE`, the `/* WARNING: ... */` wrapper, and the block layout\n51\t  (`render_report`, report.rs:41-57) reproduce observed oracle output verbatim\n52\t  (BEHAVIOR.md §\"Overall report shape\", captures). → **Filtered: observed output.**\n53\t- `insert_wf_before` (report.rs:61-76) has the exact signature from\n54\t  `required_api.md:23`. Its body (`position(anchor)` → `split_off` → splice) is\n55\t  the only reasonable implementation of the documented contract and differs in\n56\t  expression from `wf.rs:115-126` (clean uses `match`, wf.rs uses\n57\t  `unwrap_or(len)`). Haskell has no analogue (it builds the report by a fixed\n58\t  `concatMap`). → **Filtered: API-given signature; body forced by contract.**\n59\t\n60\t## 2. lib.rs\n61\t\n62\t- `check_theory` (lib.rs:36-56) runs the checks in the **observed** canonical\n63\t  topic order (BEHAVIOR.md §\"Canonical topic order\", ks1/ks3 probes) and then\n64\t  splices `public_names_report` via `insert_wf_before(after_public_names_topics())`.\n65\t  This run-then-splice shape matches `wf.rs:146-195` and is *not* Haskell's shape\n66\t  (Haskell simply lists `publicNamesReport` 4th in a `concatMap`,\n67\t  Wellformedness.hs:1271-1283). The shape is transmitted by the interface, which\n68\t  exposes `insert_wf_before` and `after_public_names_topics` as required API.\n69\t  → **Filtered: API-given.** (See §7 process caveat.)\n70\t- `after_public_names_topics` (lib.rs:19-33) lists topic strings — all observable\n71\t  output headers — in observed order. The clean list contains **only** the\n72\t  AST-derivable topics and omits wf.rs's `\"Fact capitalization issues\"`,\n73\t  `\"Lemma annotations\"`, `\"Multiplication restriction of rules\"`,\n74\t  `\"Message Derivation Checks\"` (wf.rs `WF_TOPIC_ORDER`, wf.rs:83-100). Divergence\n75\t  from wf.rs. → **Filtered: API-given function; content is observed topic order.**\n76\t- `check_if_lemmas_in_theory` (lib.rs:62-74) — API-given signature\n77\t  (required_api.md:19). The clean body is a plain set-difference with a\n78\t  self-documented \"message text is a gap\" (it does not reproduce Haskell's\n79\t  `checkIfLemmasInTheory` wording, Wellformedness.hs:1156-1171). → **Filtered.**\n80\t\n81\t## 3. checks.rs\n82\t\n83\tPublic check function names are all derived from the **topic strings**\n84\t(observable output): `unbound_variables`, `mismatching_sorts`, `reserved_names`,\n85\t`fr_facts`, `special_facts`, `fact_arity`, `fact_multiplicity`, `formula_terms`,\n86\t`formula_guardedness`, `nat_sorts`, `subterm_convergence`. None match Haskell's\n87\tinternal names (`unboundCheck`, `sortsClashCheck`, `reservedFactNameRules'`,\n88\t`freshFactArguments'`, `specialFactsUsage'`, `factUsage`, `checkTerms`,\n89\t`checkGuarded`, `natWellSortedReport`, `checkEquationsSubtermConvergence`) and\n90\tnone match wf.rs's internal names (`unbound_report`, `variable_sort_clashes`,\n91\t`reserved_fact_name_rules`, `fresh_fact_arguments`, `special_facts_usage`,\n92\t`fact_usage`, `nat_well_sorted_report`, `subterm_convergence_report`).\n93\t→ **Filtered: names derived from observable topics.**\n94\t\n95\tInternal helpers (`collect_term_vars`, `collect_fact_vars`, `collect_pub_lits`,\n96\t`var_key`, `sort_rank`, `dedup_vars`, `variant_repr`, `gather_fact_uses`,\n97\t`render_fact_blocks`, `nearest_rhs`, `edit_distance`, `free_vars_formula`,\n98\t`atom_vars`, `guard_vars`, `find_unguarded`, `collect_nat_issues`, `is_subterm`,\n99\t`FactUse`, `FactId`, `protocol_rules`, `is_reserved`/`is_special`/\n100\t`is_builtin_factname`) — none share a name with a Haskell internal. Per-check\n101\tnotes:\n102\t\n103\t- **Unbound variables** (checks.rs:132-176): message text is observed\n104\t  (BEHAVIOR.md §Unbound; probes p01/ub_pub/z5). The bound/used partition\n105\t  (bound = premises ∪ let-bound; used = actions ∪ conclusions ∪ let-RHS) and the\n106\t  `var_needs_binding` set {Fresh, Msg, Untagged, Nat} **diverge** from Haskell\n107\t  `unboundCheck` (Wellformedness.hs:493-511), which excludes only `LSortPub` and\n108\t  the special `NOW` node and has no explicit let handling (it relies on already-\n109\t  substituted facts + `originatesFromLookup`). Clean excludes `Node` entirely and\n110\t  handles `let` explicitly. → **Filtered: not Haskell's expression; observable.**\n111\t- **Mismatching sorts** (checks.rs:181-241): header text observed (p20/ms2,\n112\t  BEHAVIOR.md:86). Clean groups by `to_lowercase(name)` with variant =\n113\t  sort-prefix+name (index ignored). Haskell `sortsClashCheck`/`clashesOn`\n114\t  (Wellformedness.hs:154-161, 258-272) groups by `(lowerCase name, idx)` with\n115\t  variant = full `LVar`. Different normalization keys. → **Filtered.**\n116\t- **Reserved names** (checks.rs:246-277): position-dependent reserved sets\n117\t  ({K,KU,KD} on L/R; +{In,Out,Fr} in the middle) and the phrase strings are\n118\t  explicitly observed (QUERIES.log z9/z11/z12; BEHAVIOR.md §Reserved names).\n119\t  → **Filtered: observed output + behavior.**\n120\t- **Fr facts / Special facts** (checks.rs:282-348): trigger conditions and the\n121\t  `on left-hand-side:` / `on right-hand-side:` / lowercase-`rule` wording are\n122\t  observed (p14/p15/sf_pos/z12; BEHAVIOR.md). → **Filtered.**\n123\t- **Fact arity / multiplicity** (checks.rs:399-471): intro strings and the\n124\t  numbered block layout are observed (p02/p03/f_arity3; BEHAVIOR.md:112-121).\n125\t  Clean shares one `gather_fact_uses` + `render_fact_blocks` across both checks;\n126\t  Haskell shares one `theoryFacts`/`allClashes` across cap/arity/mult\n127\t  (Wellformedness.hs:636-689). This shared-grouping shape is the natural\n128\t  consequence of both checks keying on per-fact-name grouping (behavior), and the\n129\t  clean side factors the two *formatters* into one shared helper whereas Haskell\n130\t  keeps `formatArityIssue`/`formatMultipIssue` separate. → **Filtered: behavior-\n131\t  driven DRY; decomposition differs from Haskell.**\n132\t- **fact_lhs_occur_no_rhs** (checks.rs:500-582): API-given name\n133\t  (required_api.md:20). Identity triple `(name, arity, persistent)` is literally\n134\t  printed in the output line (`factName \\`X' arity: N multiplicity: Linear`), so\n135\t  it is observation-derived, not lifted from Haskell's `factInfo`\n136\t  (Wellformedness.hs:174-175). The `edit_distance ≤ 3` suggestion threshold and\n137\t  \"nearest RHS by name distance\" behavior are observed (th2/thN; BEHAVIOR.md:128).\n138\t  `edit_distance` is textbook two-row Levenshtein; the name is generic. Clean's\n139\t  index numbering does **not** left-pad to width (unlike wf.rs `numbered_index_\n140\t  width`, wf.rs:1353/431), a divergence. → **Filtered.**\n141\t- **Public names** (checks.rs:588-654): API-given `public_names_report` /\n142\t  `public_names_report_from_pairs` (required_api.md:21-22). Header text observed\n143\t  (p32/p38; BEHAVIOR.md:74-81). Clean's pair order is **`(name, rule)`** — the\n144\t  *opposite* of wf.rs's **`(rule, name)`** (wf.rs:1455) — and clean groups by\n145\t  first-seen order, whereas both Haskell (`clashesOn` → `sortOn`) and wf.rs sort\n146\t  by lowercased name. Strong divergence. → **Filtered; independence evidence.**\n147\t- **Formula terms** (checks.rs:657-755): the `` `Free x' `` rendering was\n148\t  observed live (QUERIES.log p05 `-> \"Formula terms\" (\\`Free y')`), and the help\n149\t  text appears in `oracle/captures/…Typing_and_Destructors…out`. Clean tracks a\n150\t  binder stack (`free_vars_formula` push/pop on quantifiers) because\n151\t  `ast_types.rs` represents quantified vars by *name* (`Forall(Vec<VarSpec>,…)`),\n152\t  not de Bruijn — so the stack is forced by the data model. Haskell `checkTerms`\n153\t  (Wellformedness.hs:960-985) needs no stack because its LNFormula already carries\n154\t  `Bound`/`Free`. `atom_vars` (checks.rs:696-712) maps each `Atom` variant to its\n155\t  constituent terms — forced by the `Atom` enum in `ast_types.rs:311-320` — and\n156\t  even diverges from Haskell `atomTerms` (Wellformedness.hs:908-915) by including\n157\t  predicate-atom facts (Haskell returns `[]` for `Syntactic`). → **Filtered.**\n158\t- **Formula guardedness** (checks.rs:761-836): the message body\n159\t  (\"cannot be converted to a guarded formula\" / \"unguarded variable(s) … in the\n160\t  subformula … in the formula\") is documented as observed (QUERIES.log\n161\t  p21/p39; BEHAVIOR.md:140-145). The detection (`find_unguarded`/`guard_vars`:\n162\t  a quantifier is \"guarded\" if its bound vars all appear under some Action/Pred\n163\t  atom) is a self-declared partial heuristic and is nothing like Haskell's real\n164\t  `formulaToGuarded` conversion. → **Filtered: observed output; own algorithm.**\n165\t- **Nat Sorts** (checks.rs:842-888): message observed (t_nat; BEHAVIOR.md:147).\n166\t  Clean collects offending *vars* (sort ≠ Nat) under a `%+`; Haskell\n167\t  `nonWellSorted` (Wellformedness.hs:293-304) collects offending *terms* recursing\n168\t  through nested nat-plus. Different traversal. → **Filtered.**\n169\t- **Subterm convergence** (checks.rs:894-930): intro + manual-URL string appears\n170\t  in captures (OIDC/POIDC/eccDAA). `is_subterm` is a self-declared structural\n171\t  approximation, unrelated to Haskell's `filterNonSubtermCtxtRule`. → **Filtered.**\n172\t\n173\t## 4. pretty.rs\n174\t\n175\tEvery rule traces to an observed probe (t_terms/t_xor/t_nat/f_nullary;\n176\tBEHAVIOR.md §\"Term pretty-printer\"). Sort sigils `~ $ % #`, pair flattening\n177\t`<…>`, `f(a, b)`, `'lit'`, `^` without parens, AC operators parenthesized,\n178\t`%1`, and `DH_neutral` (present in `oracle/captures/…RYY_PFS…out`) are all\n179\tobserved output. Independent-derivation signals vs. wf.rs:\n180\t\n181\t- `Term::NumberOne => \"1\"` (pretty.rs:87) vs. wf.rs `NumberOne => \"one\"`\n182\t  (wf.rs:466). **Opposite rendering.**\n183\t- Only `Xor` operands are sorted, by **rendered-string** sort (pretty.rs:71-74);\n184\t  wf.rs sorts **all** AC operators (Mult/Union/Xor/NatPlus) by a term `Ord`\n185\t  (`cmp_wf_term`, wf.rs:517-521). Different scope and different comparator.\n186\t\n187\t→ **Filtered: observed output; clear divergence from wf.rs.**\n188\t\n189\t## 5. formula.rs\n190\t\n191\tSingle-line unicode printer `pp_formula` (formula.rs:10-42). Operator glyphs\n192\t(⊥ ⊤ ¬ ∧ ∨ ⇒ ⇔ ∀ ∃ = < ⋖ ⊏ @ last(…)) are formula-rendering output; the\n193\tmodule header states it was \"calibrated from the oracle (e.g. ks1 lemma L2)\".\n194\tClean **fully parenthesizes** every binary connective (`({}) ∧ ({})`), unlike\n195\tHaskell's precedence-minimized `prettyLNFormula`. → **Filtered: observed/\n196\tcalibrated; own parenthesization.** (`⋖` LessMset / `⊏` Subterm may be rarer in\n197\tthe probed lemmas, but both are standard notation and the module is declared a\n198\tdocumented partial; not worth a redo.)\n199\t\n200\t## 6. Secondary check — divergence from replaced `wf.rs`\n201\t\n202\tInstruction: flag only where clean matches `wf.rs` structure in ways Haskell and\n203\tbehavior do not explain. **Result: no such match.** Every clean/wf.rs match is\n204\tcovered by `required_api.md` (WfError, new, WfReport, insert_wf_before,\n205\tafter_public_names_topics, public_names_report[_from_pairs], topics,\n206\tunderline_topic, render_report, check_theory, check_if_lemmas_in_theory,\n207\tfact_lhs_occur_no_rhs). The clean code diverges from wf.rs everywhere the API is\n208\tsilent:\n209\t\n210\t| Aspect | clean | wf.rs |\n211\t|---|---|---|\n212\t| `_from_pairs` tuple order | `(name, rule)` | `(rule, name)` |\n213\t| public-names grouping | first-seen order | sorted (`clashesOn`) |\n214\t| `NumberOne` render | `\"1\"` | `\"one\"` |\n215\t| AC operand sort | Xor only, string sort | all AC, term `Ord` |\n216\t| `underline_topic` trailing `\\n` | none | present |\n217\t| numbered index padding | none | width-padded |\n218\t| internal sort order (`sort_rank`) | Msg<Pub<Fresh<Node<Nat | Pub<Fresh<Msg<Node<Nat |\n219\t| check fn names | topic-derived | port-derived |\n220\t\n221\tNo Haskell-internal identifiers or `.hs:` source citations appear anywhere in the\n222\tclean sources (grep confirmed empty).\n223\t\n224\t## 7. Process caveat (NOT a clean-side violation; no redo)\n225\t\n226\t`required_api.md` hands the clean room three functions whose *existence* is a\n227\tport-specific implementation seam with **no behavioral justification derivable\n228\tfrom the oracle**: `insert_wf_before`, `after_public_names_topics`, and the\n229\t`public_names_report` / `public_names_report_from_pairs` split. The oracle never\n230\texposes these seams; the clean room implemented them only because the interface\n231\trequired them. Per the protocol these are \"API names given in the provided\n232\tinterface docs\" and are explicitly *not* clean-room violations, so no redo is\n233\tissued to `wf-clean`. This is flagged upward to the process owners: the\n234\tinteroperability header for future clusters should prefer conveying *behavior/\n235\tordering* over port-internal function decompositions, to keep the clean room from\n236\tinheriting the port's architecture. The clean implementations of these functions\n237\tare, in any case, independently expressed (see §1, §2, §3).\n238\t"}]},"uuid":"31227404-2e69-40aa-8185-230919b7e69f","timestamp":"2026-07-17T12:16:44.205Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/kamilner/tamarin-cleanroom/wellformedness/AUDIT.md","content":"# Similarity audit — wellformedness cluster (`wf-clean`)\n\nAuditor role: clean-room similarity review. I read both the clean side and the\nGPL Haskell originals (and, as a secondary leak check, the replaced Rust module\n`crates/tamarin-parser/src/wf.rs`). Method: abstraction–filtration–comparison.\n\n- CLEAN SIDE: `workspace/wf-clean/src/{pretty,report,checks,formula,lib}.rs`\n  (`ast.rs` is the provided interface header — not audited).\n- HASKELL: `tamarin-prover/lib/theory/src/Theory/Tools/Wellformedness.hs`\n  (+ its pretty-printing dependencies).\n- INTERFACE GIVEN TO CLEAN ROOM: `interface/required_api.md`,\n  `interface/ast_types.rs`, `SPEC.md`.\n- CLEAN-ROOM EVIDENCE OF DERIVATION: `workspace/QUERIES.log` (per-probe oracle\n  interaction log), `workspace/BEHAVIOR.md` (inferred behavioral spec),\n  `oracle/captures/*.out` (37 pre-captured oracle outputs).\n\n## Verdict\n\n**PASS. No violations survive filtration.** Every clean/Haskell (or\nclean/wf.rs) similarity resolves to one of the three filtered categories:\n(a) a name or signature explicitly listed in `required_api.md`; (b) an exact\nmessage string present in observed oracle output (captures) or logged as a live\noracle observation in `QUERIES.log`/`BEHAVIOR.md`; or (c) structure forced by\nthe `ast_types.rs` data model or by the block/underline output format.\n\nThe clean code additionally *diverges* from `wf.rs` at every point the interface\ndoes not constrain (see §6), which is positive evidence of independent\nderivation rather than reproduction. One **process caveat** (not a clean-side\nauthorship violation, no redo) is recorded in §7: the interface header transmits\na port-specific function decomposition to the clean room.\n\n---\n\n## 1. report.rs\n\n- `WfError { topic: String, message: String }`, `impl WfError::new(topic: impl\n  Into<String>, message: impl Into<String>)`, and `pub type WfReport =\n  Vec<WfError>` (report.rs:7-22) are **byte-for-byte the surface in\n  `required_api.md:4-6`**. Haskell models this as `type WfError = (Topic, Doc)` /\n  `type WfErrorReport = [WfError]` (Wellformedness.hs:112-114). The struct field\n  name `message` and the shortened `WfReport` come from the interface header, not\n  from Haskell (which has an unnamed `Doc` and `WfErrorReport`).\n  → **Filtered: API names given in interface docs.**\n- `underline_topic` (report.rs:29-33) renders `title + \"\\n\" + \"=\"*n`. Haskell\n  `underlineTopic` (Wellformedness.hs:168-171) and `wf.rs:400-408` BOTH append a\n  trailing `\"\\n\"`; the clean version does **not** — it assembles the blank line\n  between header and body in `render_block`/`render_report` instead. Divergence\n  from both prior implementations; behavior (the `=` underline) is observable.\n  → **Filtered (observed); note the divergence as independence evidence.**\n- `SUCCESS_LINE`, the `/* WARNING: ... */` wrapper, and the block layout\n  (`render_report`, report.rs:41-57) reproduce observed oracle output verbatim\n  (BEHAVIOR.md §\"Overall report shape\", captures). → **Filtered: observed output.**\n- `insert_wf_before` (report.rs:61-76) has the exact signature from\n  `required_api.md:23`. Its body (`position(anchor)` → `split_off` → splice) is\n  the only reasonable implementation of the documented contract and differs in\n  expression from `wf.rs:115-126` (clean uses `match`, wf.rs uses\n  `unwrap_or(len)`). Haskell has no analogue (it builds the report by a fixed\n  `concatMap`). → **Filtered: API-given signature; body forced by contract.**\n\n## 2. lib.rs\n\n- `check_theory` (lib.rs:36-56) runs the checks in the **observed** canonical\n  topic order (BEHAVIOR.md §\"Canonical topic order\", ks1/ks3 probes) and then\n  splices `public_names_report` via `insert_wf_before(after_public_names_topics())`.\n  This run-then-splice shape matches `wf.rs:146-195` and is *not* Haskell's shape\n  (Haskell simply lists `publicNamesReport` 4th in a `concatMap`,\n  Wellformedness.hs:1271-1283). The shape is transmitted by the interface, which\n  exposes `insert_wf_before` and `after_public_names_topics` as required API.\n  → **Filtered: API-given.** (See §7 process caveat.)\n- `after_public_names_topics` (lib.rs:19-33) lists topic strings — all observable\n  output headers — in observed order. The clean list contains **only** the\n  AST-derivable topics and omits wf.rs's `\"Fact capitalization issues\"`,\n  `\"Lemma annotations\"`, `\"Multiplication restriction of rules\"`,\n  `\"Message Derivation Checks\"` (wf.rs `WF_TOPIC_ORDER`, wf.rs:83-100). Divergence\n  from wf.rs. → **Filtered: API-given function; content is observed topic order.**\n- `check_if_lemmas_in_theory` (lib.rs:62-74) — API-given signature\n  (required_api.md:19). The clean body is a plain set-difference with a\n  self-documented \"message text is a gap\" (it does not reproduce Haskell's\n  `checkIfLemmasInTheory` wording, Wellformedness.hs:1156-1171). → **Filtered.**\n\n## 3. checks.rs\n\nPublic check function names are all derived from the **topic strings**\n(observable output): `unbound_variables`, `mismatching_sorts`, `reserved_names`,\n`fr_facts`, `special_facts`, `fact_arity`, `fact_multiplicity`, `formula_terms`,\n`formula_guardedness`, `nat_sorts`, `subterm_convergence`. None match Haskell's\ninternal names (`unboundCheck`, `sortsClashCheck`, `reservedFactNameRules'`,\n`freshFactArguments'`, `specialFactsUsage'`, `factUsage`, `checkTerms`,\n`checkGuarded`, `natWellSortedReport`, `checkEquationsSubtermConvergence`) and\nnone match wf.rs's internal names (`unbound_report`, `variable_sort_clashes`,\n`reserved_fact_name_rules`, `fresh_fact_arguments`, `special_facts_usage`,\n`fact_usage`, `nat_well_sorted_report`, `subterm_convergence_report`).\n→ **Filtered: names derived from observable topics.**\n\nInternal helpers (`collect_term_vars`, `collect_fact_vars`, `collect_pub_lits`,\n`var_key`, `sort_rank`, `dedup_vars`, `variant_repr`, `gather_fact_uses`,\n`render_fact_blocks`, `nearest_rhs`, `edit_distance`, `free_vars_formula`,\n`atom_vars`, `guard_vars`, `find_unguarded`, `collect_nat_issues`, `is_subterm`,\n`FactUse`, `FactId`, `protocol_rules`, `is_reserved`/`is_special`/\n`is_builtin_factname`) — none share a name with a Haskell internal. Per-check\nnotes:\n\n- **Unbound variables** (checks.rs:132-176): message text is observed\n  (BEHAVIOR.md §Unbound; probes p01/ub_pub/z5). The bound/used partition\n  (bound = premises ∪ let-bound; used = actions ∪ conclusions ∪ let-RHS) and the\n  `var_needs_binding` set {Fresh, Msg, Untagged, Nat} **diverge** from Haskell\n  `unboundCheck` (Wellformedness.hs:493-511), which excludes only `LSortPub` and\n  the special `NOW` node and has no explicit let handling (it relies on already-\n  substituted facts + `originatesFromLookup`). Clean excludes `Node` entirely and\n  handles `let` explicitly. → **Filtered: not Haskell's expression; observable.**\n- **Mismatching sorts** (checks.rs:181-241): header text observed (p20/ms2,\n  BEHAVIOR.md:86). Clean groups by `to_lowercase(name)` with variant =\n  sort-prefix+name (index ignored). Haskell `sortsClashCheck`/`clashesOn`\n  (Wellformedness.hs:154-161, 258-272) groups by `(lowerCase name, idx)` with\n  variant = full `LVar`. Different normalization keys. → **Filtered.**\n- **Reserved names** (checks.rs:246-277): position-dependent reserved sets\n  ({K,KU,KD} on L/R; +{In,Out,Fr} in the middle) and the phrase strings are\n  explicitly observed (QUERIES.log z9/z11/z12; BEHAVIOR.md §Reserved names).\n  → **Filtered: observed output + behavior.**\n- **Fr facts / Special facts** (checks.rs:282-348): trigger conditions and the\n  `on left-hand-side:` / `on right-hand-side:` / lowercase-`rule` wording are\n  observed (p14/p15/sf_pos/z12; BEHAVIOR.md). → **Filtered.**\n- **Fact arity / multiplicity** (checks.rs:399-471): intro strings and the\n  numbered block layout are observed (p02/p03/f_arity3; BEHAVIOR.md:112-121).\n  Clean shares one `gather_fact_uses` + `render_fact_blocks` across both checks;\n  Haskell shares one `theoryFacts`/`allClashes` across cap/arity/mult\n  (Wellformedness.hs:636-689). This shared-grouping shape is the natural\n  consequence of both checks keying on per-fact-name grouping (behavior), and the\n  clean side factors the two *formatters* into one shared helper whereas Haskell\n  keeps `formatArityIssue`/`formatMultipIssue` separate. → **Filtered: behavior-\n  driven DRY; decomposition differs from Haskell.**\n- **fact_lhs_occur_no_rhs** (checks.rs:500-582): API-given name\n  (required_api.md:20). Identity triple `(name, arity, persistent)` is literally\n  printed in the output line (`factName \\`X' arity: N multiplicity: Linear`), so\n  it is observation-derived, not lifted from Haskell's `factInfo`\n  (Wellformedness.hs:174-175). The `edit_distance ≤ 3` suggestion threshold and\n  \"nearest RHS by name distance\" behavior are observed (th2/thN; BEHAVIOR.md:128).\n  `edit_distance` is textbook two-row Levenshtein; the name is generic. Clean's\n  index numbering does **not** left-pad to width (unlike wf.rs `numbered_index_\n  width`, wf.rs:1353/431), a divergence. → **Filtered.**\n- **Public names** (checks.rs:588-654): API-given `public_names_report` /\n  `public_names_report_from_pairs` (required_api.md:21-22). Header text observed\n  (p32/p38; BEHAVIOR.md:74-81). Clean's pair order is **`(name, rule)`** — the\n  *opposite* of wf.rs's **`(rule, name)`** (wf.rs:1455) — and clean groups by\n  first-seen order, whereas both Haskell (`clashesOn` → `sortOn`) and wf.rs sort\n  by lowercased name. Strong divergence. → **Filtered; independence evidence.**\n- **Formula terms** (checks.rs:657-755): the `` `Free x' `` rendering was\n  observed live (QUERIES.log p05 `-> \"Formula terms\" (\\`Free y')`), and the help\n  text appears in `oracle/captures/…Typing_and_Destructors…out`. Clean tracks a\n  binder stack (`free_vars_formula` push/pop on quantifiers) because\n  `ast_types.rs` represents quantified vars by *name* (`Forall(Vec<VarSpec>,…)`),\n  not de Bruijn — so the stack is forced by the data model. Haskell `checkTerms`\n  (Wellformedness.hs:960-985) needs no stack because its LNFormula already carries\n  `Bound`/`Free`. `atom_vars` (checks.rs:696-712) maps each `Atom` variant to its\n  constituent terms — forced by the `Atom` enum in `ast_types.rs:311-320` — and\n  even diverges from Haskell `atomTerms` (Wellformedness.hs:908-915) by including\n  predicate-atom facts (Haskell returns `[]` for `Syntactic`). → **Filtered.**\n- **Formula guardedness** (checks.rs:761-836): the message body\n  (\"cannot be converted to a guarded formula\" / \"unguarded variable(s) … in the\n  subformula … in the formula\") is documented as observed (QUERIES.log\n  p21/p39; BEHAVIOR.md:140-145). The detection (`find_unguarded`/`guard_vars`:\n  a quantifier is \"guarded\" if its bound vars all appear under some Action/Pred\n  atom) is a self-declared partial heuristic and is nothing like Haskell's real\n  `formulaToGuarded` conversion. → **Filtered: observed output; own algorithm.**\n- **Nat Sorts** (checks.rs:842-888): message observed (t_nat; BEHAVIOR.md:147).\n  Clean collects offending *vars* (sort ≠ Nat) under a `%+`; Haskell\n  `nonWellSorted` (Wellformedness.hs:293-304) collects offending *terms* recursing\n  through nested nat-plus. Different traversal. → **Filtered.**\n- **Subterm convergence** (checks.rs:894-930): intro + manual-URL string appears\n  in captures (OIDC/POIDC/eccDAA). `is_subterm` is a self-declared structural\n  approximation, unrelated to Haskell's `filterNonSubtermCtxtRule`. → **Filtered.**\n\n## 4. pretty.rs\n\nEvery rule traces to an observed probe (t_terms/t_xor/t_nat/f_nullary;\nBEHAVIOR.md §\"Term pretty-printer\"). Sort sigils `~ $ % #`, pair flattening\n`<…>`, `f(a, b)`, `'lit'`, `^` without parens, AC operators parenthesized,\n`%1`, and `DH_neutral` (present in `oracle/captures/…RYY_PFS…out`) are all\nobserved output. Independent-derivation signals vs. wf.rs:\n\n- `Term::NumberOne => \"1\"` (pretty.rs:87) vs. wf.rs `NumberOne => \"one\"`\n  (wf.rs:466). **Opposite rendering.**\n- Only `Xor` operands are sorted, by **rendered-string** sort (pretty.rs:71-74);\n  wf.rs sorts **all** AC operators (Mult/Union/Xor/NatPlus) by a term `Ord`\n  (`cmp_wf_term`, wf.rs:517-521). Different scope and different comparator.\n\n→ **Filtered: observed output; clear divergence from wf.rs.**\n\n## 5. formula.rs\n\nSingle-line unicode printer `pp_formula` (formula.rs:10-42). Operator glyphs\n(⊥ ⊤ ¬ ∧ ∨ ⇒ ⇔ ∀ ∃ = < ⋖ ⊏ @ last(…)) are formula-rendering output; the\nmodule header states it was \"calibrated from the oracle (e.g. ks1 lemma L2)\".\nClean **fully parenthesizes** every binary connective (`({}) ∧ ({})`), unlike\nHaskell's precedence-minimized `prettyLNFormula`. → **Filtered: observed/\ncalibrated; own parenthesization.** (`⋖` LessMset / `⊏` Subterm may be rarer in\nthe probed lemmas, but both are standard notation and the module is declared a\ndocumented partial; not worth a redo.)\n\n## 6. Secondary check — divergence from replaced `wf.rs`\n\nInstruction: flag only where clean matches `wf.rs` structure in ways Haskell and\nbehavior do not explain. **Result: no such match.** Every clean/wf.rs match is\ncovered by `required_api.md` (WfError, new, WfReport, insert_wf_before,\nafter_public_names_topics, public_names_report[_from_pairs], topics,\nunderline_topic, render_report, check_theory, check_if_lemmas_in_theory,\nfact_lhs_occur_no_rhs). The clean code diverges from wf.rs everywhere the API is\nsilent:\n\n| Aspect | clean | wf.rs |\n|---|---|---|\n| `_from_pairs` tuple order | `(name, rule)` | `(rule, name)` |\n| public-names grouping | first-seen order | sorted (`clashesOn`) |\n| `NumberOne` render | `\"1\"` | `\"one\"` |\n| AC operand sort | Xor only, string sort | all AC, term `Ord` |\n| `underline_topic` trailing `\\n` | none | present |\n| numbered index padding | none | width-padded |\n| internal sort order (`sort_rank`) | Msg<Pub<Fresh<Node<Nat | Pub<Fresh<Msg<Node<Nat |\n| check fn names | topic-derived | port-derived |\n\nNo Haskell-internal identifiers or `.hs:` source citations appear anywhere in the\nclean sources (grep confirmed empty).\n\n## 7. Process caveat (NOT a clean-side violation; no redo)\n\n`required_api.md` hands the clean room three functions whose *existence* is a\nport-specific implementation seam with **no behavioral justification derivable\nfrom the oracle**: `insert_wf_before`, `after_public_names_topics`, and the\n`public_names_report` / `public_names_report_from_pairs` split. The oracle never\nexposes these seams; the clean room implemented them only because the interface\nrequired them. Per the protocol these are \"API names given in the provided\ninterface docs\" and are explicitly *not* clean-room violations, so no redo is\nissued to `wf-clean`. This is flagged upward to the process owners: the\ninteroperability header for future clusters should prefer conveying *behavior/\nordering* over port-internal function decompositions, to keep the clean room from\ninheriting the port's architecture. The clean implementations of these functions\nare, in any case, independently expressed (see §1, §2, §3).\n","numLines":238,"startLine":1,"totalLines":238}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"f7ce944e-e0cc-4459-9b56-e427eed09195","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/home/kamilner/tamarin-rs","sessionId":"57f8e1bc-d495-4b36-93c0-033347d5034a","version":"2.1.212","gitBranch":"main"}
